Note:
BF #362 regression test: string_to_float must produce the correctly-
rounded IEEE 754 binary64 bit pattern for decimal-literal inputs.

The previous implementation in runtime/integration/runtime_api.runa
scaled the parsed mantissa by repeated multiplication against
0.1 (= 0x3FB999999999999A, itself a one-ULP-rounded approximation
of the mathematical value 1/10). After even a single such multiply
the accumulated error pushed many results one ULP above the
correctly-rounded value. The canonical witness is "0.3":

    Previous string_to_float("0.3") = 0x3FD3333333333334   (WRONG, +1 ULP)
    Correct string_to_float("0.3")  = 0x3FD3333333333333

The fix uses Clinger's fast path (Clinger 1990): when |total_exp| <=
22 AND |mantissa| < 2^53, scale by a SINGLE multiplication or division
against the exact power-of-ten 10^|exp| (which is exactly representable
in binary64 for these exponents). IEEE 754 guarantees that a single
operation between two exactly-representable operands rounds to the
nearest representable value, so the result is correctly rounded.

This file exercises:
  - All BF #362 canonical failure cases (0.1, 0.2, 0.3 and friends)
  - Integer literals (3, 100, 1000)
  - Negative numbers
  - Scientific notation (positive and negative exponents)
  - Slow-path inputs (exp magnitude > 22)
  - Boundary inputs (subnormal, near-max-finite, infinity)
  - Sign handling (positive, negative, explicit '+')

Reporting follows the canonical tests/test_utils.runa convention:
each KAT is an assert_equal against the exact IEEE 754 bit pattern,
the suite prints "ALL TESTS PASSED" and exits 0 when every KAT holds,
and exits with the failure count otherwise.
:End Note

Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as T
Import "runtime/integration/runtime_api.runa" as Runtime

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be T.create_test_results()
    T.begin_suite(results, "runtime.string_to_float_rounding")

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 1: "0.3" must give 0x3FD3333333333333 = 4599075939470750515.
    Note: This is THE BF #362 canonical failure case. Previous code
    Note: returned 4599075939470750516 (+1 ULP).
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r1 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "0.3"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 1: 0.3 correctly rounded", r1, 4599075939470750515)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 2: "0.1" must give 0x3FB999999999999A = 4591870180066957722.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r2 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "0.1"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 2: 0.1 correctly rounded", r2, 4591870180066957722)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 3: "0.2" must give 0x3FC999999999999A = 4596373779694328218.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r3 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "0.2"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 3: 0.2 correctly rounded", r3, 4596373779694328218)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 4: "3.0" must give 0x4008000000000000 = 4613937818241073152.
    Note: An exact integer * 10^0 case (Clinger trivial: exp == 0).
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r4 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "3.0"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 4: 3.0 exact", r4, 4613937818241073152)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 5: "1.0" must give 0x3FF0000000000000 = 4607182418800017408.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r5 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "1.0"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 5: 1.0 exact", r5, 4607182418800017408)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 6: "0" must give +0.0 = 0.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r6 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "0"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 6: 0 is +0.0", r6, 0)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 7: "100" must give 100.0 = 0x4059000000000000 = 4636737291354636288.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r7 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "100"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 7: 100 exact", r7, 4636737291354636288)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 8: "-0.3" must give -0.3 = 0xBFD3333333333333.
    Note: Bit pattern as signed two's-complement Int64: -4624296097384025293.
    Note: Verified via Python: struct.unpack('<q', struct.pack('<d', -0.3))[0].
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r8 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "-0.3"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 8: -0.3 correctly rounded", r8, -4624296097384025293)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 9: "+0.3" with explicit positive sign must equal "0.3".
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r9 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "+0.3"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 9: +0.3 explicit sign", r9, 4599075939470750515)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 10: "1e0" via scientific notation must equal 1.0.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r10 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "1e0"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 10: 1e0 is 1.0", r10, 4607182418800017408)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 11: "1e1" via scientific notation must equal 10.0.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r11 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "1e1"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 11: 1e1 is 10.0", r11, 4621819117588971520)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 12: "1E1" with capital E must also equal 10.0.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r12 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "1E1"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 12: 1E1 capital E", r12, 4621819117588971520)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 13: "1e-1" must equal 0.1.
    Note: This exercises the negative-exponent Clinger path (divide).
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r13 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "1e-1"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 13: 1e-1 is 0.1", r13, 4591870180066957722)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 14: "2.5e-2" = 0.025 must give 0x3F9999999999999A = 4582862980812216730.
    Note: Verified via Python: struct.unpack('<Q', struct.pack('<d', 0.025))[0].
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r14 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "2.5e-2"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 14: 2.5e-2 correctly rounded", r14, 4582862980812216730)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 15: "1e22" must give 1e22 = 0x4480F0CF064DD592 = 4936209963552724370.
    Note: Boundary of Clinger fast path - exp == 22.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r15 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "1e22"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 15: 1e22 fast-path boundary", r15, 4936209963552724370)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 16: "1e-22" must give 0x3B5E392010175EE6 = 4277919505920253670.
    Note: Boundary of Clinger fast path - exp == -22 (divide path).
    Note: Verified via Python: struct.unpack('<Q', struct.pack('<d', 1e-22))[0].
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r16 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "1e-22"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 16: 1e-22 fast-path boundary", r16, 4277919505920253670)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 17: "1e23" enters the multi-step fallback. Python value:
    Note: 0x44B52D02C7E14AF6 = 4950912855330343670.
    Note: Our fallback computes 1.0 * 1e22 * 1e1. Both factors are
    Note: exactly representable in binary64, so each mulsd is correctly
    Note: rounded and the composed result matches the correctly-rounded
    Note: target exactly.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r17 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "1e23"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 17: 1e23 fallback path", r17, 4950912855330343670)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 18: "5e-1" must give 0.5 exactly = 0x3FE0000000000000 = 4602678819172646912.
    Note: 0.5 has an exact binary64 representation; rounding must NOT
    Note: introduce error here.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r18 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "5e-1"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 18: 5e-1 is 0.5 exact", r18, 4602678819172646912)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 19: Multi-digit mantissa. "3.14159" must give
    Note: 0x400921F9F01B866E = 4614256650576692846.
    Note: Verified via Python: struct.unpack('<Q', struct.pack('<d', 3.14159))[0].
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r19 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "3.14159"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 19: 3.14159 multi-digit", r19, 4614256650576692846)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 20: Negative scientific. "-2.5e3" = -2500.0.
    Note: -2500.0 bit pattern: struct.unpack('<q', struct.pack('<d', -2500.0))[0] = -4565656063642173440.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r20 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "-2.5e3"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 20: -2.5e3 is -2500.0", r20, -4565656063642173440)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 21: Zero with decimal. "0.0" must equal 0.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r21 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "0.0"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 21: 0.0 is +0.0", r21, 0)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 22: Integer with trailing dot. "5." must equal 5.0.
    Note: 5.0 = 0x4014000000000000 = 4617315517961601024.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r22 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "5."
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 22: 5. trailing dot", r22, 4617315517961601024)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 23: Decimal-only ".5" must equal 0.5.
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r23 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with ".5"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 23: .5 leading dot", r23, 4602678819172646912)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 24: Many fraction digits. "0.123456789012345" must give
    Note: 0x3FBF9ADD3746F62E = 4593560419847042606 (banker-rounded to
    Note: 15 significant decimal digits, which is well within Float64's
    Note: 15-17 decimal precision band).
    Note: Verified via Python: struct.unpack('<Q', struct.pack('<d', 0.123456789012345))[0].
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r24 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "0.123456789012345"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 24: 0.123456789012345 long mantissa", r24, 4593560419847042606)

    Note: ============================================================
    Note: KAT 25: "6.022e23" Avogadro's number. Mantissa 6022 fits in
    Note: 53 bits, total exp = -3 + 23 = 20, |exp| = 20 <= 22, so
    Note: Clinger fast path applies. Bit pattern:
    Note: 0x44DFE154F457EA13 = 4962933069378480659.
    Note: Verified via Python: struct.unpack('<Q', struct.pack('<d', 6.022e23))[0].
    Note: ============================================================
    Let r25 be proc string_to_float from Runtime with "6.022e23"
    T.assert_equal(results, "KAT 25: 6.022e23 Avogadro", r25, 4962933069378480659)

    T.print_summary(results)
    Let exit_code be T.get_failed(results)
    T.destroy_test_results(results)
    Return exit_code
End Process
